William the seventh's son was the eighth William Davenport who acquired the estate in 1696, and an inventory of his property made shortly after his death in 1706 shows the gallery and gatehouse of Bramall were still intact.
He and Maria moved from Bramall to Cheltenham in 1841, most likely because living at Bramall had become expensive or because of health concerns.
Maria continued to own the property at Bramall in her name from 1845 until 1854 .
Her eldest son, William Davenport Davenport inherited the property in 1854 and was married firstly to Camilla Maria Gatt, then secondly to Diana Handley, whom he lived with at Bramall for four years before the estate was passed to him.
During William's tenure Bramall was regularly visited by members of the public, and the Chapel continued to be used for regular services of worship.
John WH Davenport returned to Bramall briefly in late 1876 at the age of 25, but on 24 January 1877 it was announced that the estate was to be sold.
The furniture was auctioned off, and the house itself and rest of the Bramall estate (totalling 1,918 acres) was sold to the Freeholders Company Limited, a Manchester property development firm, on 3 August 1877 for £200,000 (about £14 million as of 2013).
Much of the Bramall estate land was sold off by the Freeholders Company but Bramhall Hall itself could neither attract a buyer nor tenant.
During that decade rumours arose that Bramall would be dismantled and transported to the United States; this may have been popularised by the autobiography of Kate Douglas Wiggin which described the author's visit to Bramall in 1890.
However, one of those present, John Henry Davies, president of Manchester United, was keen to "save" the historic property and later offered £15,000 for the house and this was accepted.
It was restored to resemble how it would have been when the Davenports were last at Bramall, and a service of consecration was held on 30 October 1938 once the work had been completed.
In 1947, an association called the Friends of Bramall Hall was set up, primarily to find furnishings for the house, but also to advise and assist in the upkeep of the house and grounds.
